frameDefinitions: A Figure is characterized as near the Ground, according to some contextually given scale.
A Self-moving Escapee departs from an Undesirable_location.
An Event takes place despite the existence of an Adversity that would otherwise support Contrary_circumstances or results.   '' 'He finished the race despite his ankle breaking.
A Figure is located in contact with a Ground.
A Rider is being transported in a Vehicle, or is moving on foot.
A Figure is located in the interior (the Profiled_region--see Locative_relation frame) of the Ground.
frameExamples: She put her shoes <t>under</t> the table .
He finished the race <t>despite</t> his ankle breaking.
There was a tight-fitting lid <t>on</t> the bottle .
<t>Mounted</t> police officers are a common sight in this village.
The bookmark <t>inside</t> her book was torn and written on .
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location. The figure can be an entity or an event.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
The <fex name='Undesirable_location'>Undesirable_location</fex> is where the Escapee begins.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the escaping occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the Escaping occurs.
The <fen>Event</fen> that occurs despite an <fen>Adversity</fen> that would seem to contradict the possibility of its occurence.
The <fen>Adversity</fen> is a state of affairs or entity that hinders or negatively affects the <fen>Event</fen>.
The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location. The figure can be an entity or an event.
The <fen>Figures</fen> are items which mutually serve to identify the location of each other.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
The <fen>Rider</fen> is being transported by a <fen>Vehicle</fen>.
The <fen>Figure</fen> is the entity located with respect to the <fen>Ground</fen>.
The <fen>Ground</fen> is the area that the <fen>Figure</fen> is located in.
The area or zone interior to the <fen>Ground</fen>.  This role excludes <fen>Figure</fen> and is only used in particular constructions such as the following:
The time during which the <fen>Figure</fen> was located in the <fen>Ground</fen>.
listRoleExamples: The cat is next to <fex>the mat</fex>.
<fex>The cat</fex> is next to the mat.
He was by the park <fex>on Friday</fex>.
He was against the wall <fex>on Friday</fex>.
Inside the cupboard was <fex>a good place to hide</fex> .
